The Ontology of DTD and C-PTSD 
10 May 2026

Jargon
Developmental Trauma Disorder (DTD); Complex Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder (C-PTSD); Intellectual Disability, or Individual Difference (ID); World Health Organistation (WHO); Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD, autistic); Restricted and Repetitive Behaviours (RRBs); Sensory Processing Disorder (SPD, not part of offical psychiatric taxnomies); Differential Diagnosis (DDx); American Psychiatric Assocaition (APA); Diagnostic and Statics Manual (DSM, by the APA); International Classification of Diseases (ICD, by the WHO); Hierarchical Taxonomy of Psychopathology (HiTOP, by the HiTOP consortium); National Institute for Mental health (NIMH, American); Research Domain Criteria (RDoC, by the NIMH); Psychodynamic Diagnostic Manual (PDM, by a psychodynamic coalition); dichotomous classification (seperating disorders into two discrete categories - ill or well); Neurodevelopmental Disorders (NDD); American Psychoanalytic Association (APsA); Personality Disorders (PDs); Trans-Diagnostic Factors (TDF)

Preamble
Aim. I believe the way DTD and C-PTSD are described by laypeople and those who write articles on the subject leads to faulty conclusions [evidence?] due to the lack of understanding by the intended audience (laypeople). In this article I aim to elucidate the scientifically-backed ontology of DTD and C-PTSD for audiences without ID.

Diagnostic systems. In Western countries†, there are 5 main dianogistic taxonomies currently in use: the DSM, the ICD, the PDM, the HiTOP, and the RDoC. 
  The DSM is the most universal, used globally [evidence?]. It is a dichotomous classification, seperating disorders into discrete categories - ill or well. It is used by many mental health professionals as well as legal and insurance systems and regulatory agencies. 
  The ICD-11 Ch. 6 ('Mental, behavioural [sic] or NDD'), is used internationally to a lesser extent than the DSM [evidence?], is internationally and freely published online. It aims to be omnicultural to a greater extent than the DSM [evidence?]. It is used by many mental health professionals as well as legal and insurance systems and regulatory agencies, though to a lesser extent than the DSM [evidence?]. Notable taxonomical differences include the inclusion/disclusion of certain diagnosis and the dimensionality of PDs. 
  The PDM aims to be an adjunct, dimensional system to complement the descriptive systems of the DSM and ICD. It organises psychopathology according to developmental stages and evaluates patients across several axes, including mental functioning (M Axis), personality organisation and syndromes (P Axis), and subjective symptom experience (S Axis).
  Finally, the HiTOP and RDoC are both dimensional models, meaning that they do not code discrete psychiatric illnesses or impairments, but the underlying, TDFs overlying unique presentations. These models are mainly used by researchers, as they can be difficult to operationalise in routine clinical practice.

Diagnostic criteria versus common elements. Diagnostic criteria is required for a diagnosis. Should a single criterion be absent, another diagnosis should be made, or, by the clinicians discretion, specifiers attached - however many diagnosis are polythetic. Common elements, as I definte them (sequelae and etiology), are statistical markers making diagnosis more likely, but may be caused by another condition. E.g. sensory sensitivities could be autistic RRBs, but could also be sequelae of a SPD or trauma-related avoidance. So, it is the clinicians judgement on which diagnosis should be made, emphasising the importance of a DDx.

